    "texts": [
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Previous names",
            "shortText": "<p><i>Pomatoleios krausii</i></p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_9_2125",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Identification features",
            "shortText": "<p>Very common and well-known species that builds large, flattish reefs of interwoven blue tubes and extends upwards into the mid-intertidal of rocky shores. The opening to each tube usually has a characteristic overhanging lip and the head bears two curved heads of feathery feeding appendages (the ‘radiolar crown’), which are usually attractively mottled in whites, blues and browns. An operculum is also present and is used to plug the opening of the tube when the worm withdraws. In this species the operculum is round and cup-shaped and bears a characteristic pair of wing–like projections.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_1_2126",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Adult size",
            "shortText": "<p>Body length typically about 15 mm and tube diameter about 2 mm.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_2_2127",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Distribution",
            "shortText": "<p><u>Global:</u> As currently defined this is a very widespread species found across the North Atlantic and Indo-Pacific, but recent studies have shown that it is in fact a species complex and several genetically-distinct species are involved. The original description was from South Africa though, so the local form is correctly named, although it will likely emerge that it is restricted to the region and forms found elsewhere in the Atlantic and Indo-Pacific will need to be renamed.</p><p><u>Local/Regional:</u> False Bay to Mozambique.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_3_2128",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Biology",
            "shortText": "<p>A very common and characteristic species of the mid to low intertidal of exposed rocky shores, where it constructs extensive flat reefs of hard bluish calcareous tubes. When underwater the mottled crowns of tentacles are extended to filter-feed and when disturbed these are rapidly withdrawn and the openings closed by the operculum. The reefs created by this worm provide habitat for a variety of other species.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_4_2129",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Food / prey",
            "shortText": "<p>Filter feeder, removing fine particulate material from the water passing thought the crown of tentacles.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_5_2130",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Reproduction",
            "shortText": "<p>Little is known about reproduction in this species, but sexes are separate and it is assumed that eggs and sperm are released directly into the water column, where they develop into planktonic larvae.&nbsp;</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_6_2131",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Similar species",
            "shortText": "<p>Although many other serpulid worms are found in the region and all construct calcareous tubes and have crowns of feeding tentacles, the large blue reefs formed by this species and its typically mid intertidal and exposed habitat make it fairly easy to identify in the field.&nbsp;</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_7_2132",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Further reading / References",
            "shortText": "Branch, G, Griffiths, CL, Branch, M & Beckley, L (2022). Two Oceans: A Guide to the Marine Life of Southern Africa. (Fifth edition) Struik Nature, Cape Town. (p. 74).<br><br>Day, JH (1967). A Monograph on the Polychaeta of Southern Africa. British Museum (Natural History), London, Part 2. (p. 800).<br><br>Simon, CA, van Niekerk, HH, Burghardt, I, ten Hove, HA & Kupriyanova, EK (2019) Not out of Africa: <i>Spirobranchus kraussii</i> (Baird, 1865) is not a global fouling and invasive serpulid of Indo-Pacific origin. <i>Aquatic Invasions</i>, 14(2): 221–249.",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_8_2133",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
